{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Arguably the most remarkable gap lies in how universities engage with and respond to generative AI [51].While Firat [15] investigate the perceptions of seven scholars and fourteen PhD students in four countries (i.e.",
    "Turkey, Sweden, Canada and Australia) on how educational institutions can best prepare for ChatGPT integration, Xiao et al. [56] investigate the factors influencing policy making for Generative AI in Higher Education, such as university academic reputation score, the general public and social media's attitude toward ChatGPT, being located in English-speaking country.",
    "Nevertheless, the current state of Generative AI implemented in higher educational settings is still under-examined.Xiao et al. [56] identified the existence of a ChatGPT school policy in the top 500 universities according to the Quacquarelli Symonds (QS) World University Rankings, result indicates that of the universities with ChatGPT policies, nearly two third embraced ChatGPT in teaching and learning.",
    "On the other hand, Sullivan et al. [46] conducted a content analysis of 100 news articles related to university responses and public discussions about ChatGPT in Australia, New Zealand, the United States, and the United Kingdom, Findings reveal that university responses focused primarily on concerns about academic integrity and opportunities for innovative assessment design.",
    "Nevertheless, there are no studies that specifically look into how universities respond in an Asian context, and the country has no authorised access to ChatGPT."
  ],
